  "issue_title": "[Feature] Post-merge edit detection upgrade",
  "issue_body": "\n## Summary\n\nThe post-merge edit anti-gaming check in `scoring.py` uses GitHub's `issue.updated_at` as a proxy for \"the discoverer edited the issue body after the solving PR merged.\" `updated_at` is bumped by **any** activity on the issue \u2014 bot comments, label changes, assignee changes, cross-references, reactions \u2014 none of which indicate gaming. As a result, legitimate solved issues are silently demoted to `closed_count` (losing their discovery score and hurting credibility) whenever a CI bot, triage bot, or maintainer touches the issue after merge.\n\nThe spec already acknowledges this is a temporary proxy and calls out a timeline/events API upgrade as the correct fix.\n\n## Motivation\n\n1. **False positives punish honest miners.** On any repo with active bots (Dependabot, stale-bot, label-bot, CLA bot) or chatty maintainers, every solved issue eventually gets touched post-merge. The current check turns \"solved + small amount of time passed\" into a credibility hit, which is the opposite of the intended signal.\n2. **The anti-gaming intent still matters.** Discoverers genuinely can edit the issue body or title after the PR merges to retcon scope (\"edit the target to match what was actually built\"). A precise detector for body/title edits preserves that protection without the collateral damage.\n3. **Low marginal cost.** The transferred-issue fix (bug-report-transfer-detection.md) already adds a GraphQL `timelineItems` call per candidate issue on the validator PAT. Requesting `ISSUE_BODY_EDIT` and `RenamedTitleEvent` items in the **same** query costs zero additional round-trips \u2014 the upgrade is effectively free once that infrastructure lands.\n4. **Spec alignment.** The rewards doc explicitly earmarks this as a planned upgrade; shipping it closes the gap between documented behavior and implementation.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-04-16T01:46:57.000Z",
